snippet: The success of the villagers of Wukan in ousting their local leaders and electing a new committee is unlikely to be a template for change in Chinese politics.
abstract: Wukan, China, has its first truly democratic vote in decades, if ever, and is something of a landmark of transparency in China’s opaque politics; after furious residents evicted their leaders and the local police force, they stared down cordons of police officers ringing the village for 10 days before Guangdong Province officials offered to address their grievances and let them choose a new village committee.
lead_paragraph: The success of the villagers of Wukan in ousting their local leaders and electing a new committee is unlikely to be a template for change in Chinese politics.

headline.seo: Chinese Village’s Revolution Unlikely to Be Replicated
headline.main: Protest’s Success May Not Change China
headline.print_headline: Protest Success Unlikely To Spur Change in China
